      <frequency>some</frequency>
      <avalancheSize>2</avalancheSize>
    </avalancheProblem>
    <weatherForecast/>
    <avalancheActivity>
      <highlights>The old snowpack remains quite well bonded.</highlights>
      <comment>In particular high altitudes and the high Alpine regions: Weak layers in the old snowpack can still be released in some place by winter sport participants. This applies in particular on steep shady slopes at intermediate and high altitudes. &lt;br/> Dry avalanches can in isolated cases be released by a single winter sport participant. In the regions exposed to snowfall this applies especially on very steep slopes. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> Even in moderately steep terrain there is a danger of falling on the hard snow surface.</comment>
    </avalancheActivity>
    <snowpackStructure>
      <comment>Monday: In some localities 5 to 15 cm of snow, and up to 20 cm in some localities, has fallen above approximately 1700 m. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> The weather conditions fostered a gradual strengthening of the snowpack. The old snowpack is largely stable and its surface has a melt-freeze crust that is strong in many cases. &lt;br/> Especially steep shady slopes high altitudes and the high Alpine regions: Weak layers exist in the snowpack. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> In the vicinity of peaks snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. &lt;br/> In places that are protected from the wind in all altitude zones a lot of snow is lying for the time of year. &lt;br/> &lt;br/></comment>
    </snowpackStructure>
    <travelAdvisory/>
